                        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">1. <u>Use Mnemonics:

                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Mnemonics are memory tools that are incredibly useful in remembering large pieces of information like lists, formulas and long pointers. Mnemonics are words whose letters stand for a separate word. For instance, VIBGYOR stands for the rainbow colours (Violet, Indigo, Blue, Green, Yellow, Orange and red) and BODMAS in mathematics stands for (Brackets, Orders, Division, Multiplication, Addition and Subtraction). You can be as creative as you want while creating your own mnemonics- the funnier and unique they are, the easier it will be for you to remember them.

                        
                        </p>
                        <div class="row" >
                            <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                <img alt="image" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/website%20blog%20photos%2Fstudytechblog%2F18377-NRJTRR.jpg?alt=media&token=9b27bb96-83ca-40b9-b596-967073438d2a" >
                            </div>
                            </div>
                        <br>
                        <H3 style="font-style: underline">2.<u> Create a Memory Palace:

                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            The memory palace, also known as the ‘Method of Loci’, is a creative visualisation technique you can use to remember information while learning. Memory palaces are created in familiar spatial surroundings like the rooms in your home or the pathway to school. To build a memory palace, you assign each object a piece of information in a familiar surrounding environment.
                            Let’s take an example; if you need to remember the benefits of using rainwater harvesting systems, you can assign each benefit to an object in your bedroom. Your bed can be ‘saves water’, the photograph on the wall can be ‘reduces water demand’, your study table can be ‘used for domestic purposes’, your wardrobe can be ‘preserves fresh water’ and so on. Associating familiar objects with concepts and frequently recalling them will help you remember them in your exam hall. 
                           
                        </p>

                     
                        <br>
                        <H3 style="font-style: underline">3.<u> Explain the Information in Your Own Words: 


                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            This method is one of the most well-known techniques used by people to remember what they learn. If you can explain complex concepts and theoretical topics to someone in easily comprehensible and simple words, that means you have understood it well. Whenever you study difficult concepts, try to explain them to someone (your parents, friends, soft toys, or even your pet) in simple words as if you are teaching a kid. Once you simplify the concept in your own words, you will be able to remember it well. 

                        </p>

                        <br>
                        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">4.<u> Take Brief Notes:

                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Taking brief class notes while your teacher teaches the lesson works exceptionally well in retaining the information taught in class. You can even note down short bullet points on a page while you read a chapter on your own. Taking notes by hand would help you remember the information for longer since you understood it first and then noted it down. These notes would also be immensely helpful during revisions. 

                        </p>
                        
                        <div class="row" >
                            <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                <img alt="image" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/website%20blog%20photos%2Fstudytechblog%2F2840443.jpg?alt=media&token=4e13f1b8-e95c-4f00-8561-df719f5194c2" >
                            </div>
                            </div>
                        <br>
                        <H3 style="font-style: underline">5.<u> Create Flashcards:
                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Creating flashcards is another memory tool you can use if you feel creative. You can use small flashcards for each topic and note down all the important information in small bullet points or make diagrams. You can skim through these flashcards every now and then to revise your memory on the important information pertaining to the topic. 

                        </p>
                        
                        <H3 style="font-style: underline">6.<u> Use Visual Aids (Diagrams/ Tables/ Flowcharts/ Mind Maps):



                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Representing information visually works wonders in remembering it faster and for longer durations. Our visual memory is very active, and we often remember things we see easily. When we watch a movie, we often remember the visual scenes very clearly though we may forget the precise dialogues. You can take advantage of your visual memory while studying. Organising information in the form of tables, flowcharts, mind maps, and diagrams would help you remember it for long. 

                        </p>
                        <div class="row" >
                            <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                <img alt="image" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/website%20blog%20photos%2Fstudytechblog%2F17Z_2105.w013.n001.450B.p30.450.jpg?alt=media&token=f8b8c550-7876-4e13-bb92-17002f2cab5c" >
                            </div>
                            </div>
  <br>
                        <H3 style=" font-style: underline">7.<u> Plan Multiple Revisions:
 
                        </u>
                        </H3>

                        <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                            Repetitively going through information stores it in your long-term memory, enabling you to register it for long durations. This is why you often remember the lyrics of your favourite song that you have listened to several times. So, while studying, do not try to memorise everything in a chapter at once. Instead, split your study sessions into multiple revision sessions. For instance, the first time you read a chapter, all you do is understand the content. You might register half of the information in the second reading and almost all of it in the third reading. The key is to plan short and multiple revision sessions. The more you revise, the better you remember. 
                        </p>
                       
                        <div class="row" >
                            <div class="col-lg-12 col-12" style="padding: 0 0 0 0;" >
                                <img alt="image" class="blogimg" src="https://firebasestorage.googleapis.com/v0/b/waves-36bb5.appspot.com/o/website%20blog%20photos%2Fstudytechblog%2F4119036.jpg?alt=media&token=c5f81142-bedd-4228-8ff2-8f178af29005" >
                            </div>
                            </div>
                            <br>
                            <H3 style=" font-style: underline">8.<u> Keep the Information in Sight:

 
                            </u>
                            </H3>
    
                            <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                Noting down essential concepts on a sheet and sticking them in places (like your cupboard or study table) where the information is in your sight most of the time would help you remember it easily. For instance, if you want to learn all the periodic table elements or trigonometry formulas, you can paste a copy of these concepts on your study shelf and go through it every now and then to retain the information better. 
                             </p>
                            <H3 style=" font-style: underline">9.<u> Visualise the Information 

 
                            </u>
                            </H3>
    
                            <p style="padding: 0px 0px 3% 0px;font-size: 23px;color: black; font-family: 'Times New Roman', Times, serif,';">
                                Visualising concepts and theoretical information using creativity and imagination is a great way to remember what you learn. The more creative you get with your visualisation, the better it is. For example, if you wish to learn the details of a battle as part of your history lesson, then you can visualise all the details of the battle and remember it like a visual story or short film in your mind. You can visualise the year in which the battle took place, the face of the rulers, the location, the number of casualties and so on. Remembering events, like a visual story, is the way to remember lengthy theoretical information.</p>
